    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Mahatma Gandhi</h2> 

            Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi, who later became known to the world as Mahatma Gandhi, was born on October 2, 1869, in Porbandar, a small coastal town in present-day Gujarat, India. His father, Karamchand Gandhi, served as a diwan (chief minister) of the local court, and his mother, Putlibai, was a deeply religious woman whose piety and moral values left a lasting impression on him.<br><br>

            As a child, Gandhi was quiet, shy, and serious. Though not particularly outstanding in his studies, he was known for his honesty and discipline. At the young age of thirteen, he was married to Kasturba Makhanji, following the customs of the time. She later became his steadfast companion in life and in his struggles.<br><br>

            In 1888, Gandhi traveled to London to study law. His years in England exposed him to new ideas and philosophies, especially those concerning religion, morality, and self-restraint. After returning to India in 1891, he found it difficult to establish a successful legal practice. Soon after, in 1893, he accepted an opportunity to work in South Africa, a decision that would change the course of his life.<br><br>

            In South Africa, Gandhi experienced racial discrimination firsthand. Once, he was thrown off a train at Pietermaritzburg for refusing to leave a ‚Äúwhites-only‚Äù compartment despite holding a valid first-class ticket. This incident awakened in him a determination to fight injustice through peaceful means. Over the next twenty years, he developed and practiced the principle of <em>Satyagraha</em>, meaning ‚Äútruth-force‚Äù or non-violent resistance, leading several campaigns against unjust laws and racial inequality.<br><br>

            When Gandhi returned to India in 1915, he became deeply involved in the struggle for the country‚Äôs independence from British rule. He led numerous movements, including the Champaran Satyagraha, the Non-Cooperation Movement, the Salt March, and the Quit India Movement. Gandhi‚Äôs philosophy of truth (Satya) and non-violence (Ahimsa) became the guiding principles of the Indian freedom struggle.<br><br>

            Beyond politics, Gandhi worked tirelessly for social reform. He fought against untouchability, promoted self-reliance through the spinning wheel (charkha), and encouraged unity among people of all religions and castes. His life was an example of simplicity, humility, and service to humanity.<br><br>

            India finally achieved independence on August 15, 1947, but Gandhi was deeply pained by the partition of the country, which led to widespread violence. On January 30, 1948, he was assassinated in New Delhi by Nathuram Godse, who opposed his ideals of peace and unity. Gandhi‚Äôs last words were ‚ÄúHey Ram!,‚Äù a reflection of his lifelong devotion to God and truth.<br><br>

            Mahatma Gandhi‚Äôs life and teachings continue to inspire millions across the world. His message of truth, love, and non-violence remains timeless, reminding humanity that true strength lies not in violence, but in compassion and courage.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Abraham Lincoln</h2>

            Abraham Lincoln, the 16th President of the United States of America, was born on February 12, 1809, in a small log cabin in Hardin County, Kentucky (now LaRue County). He came from a poor but hardworking family. His father, Thomas Lincoln, was a farmer and carpenter, and his mother, Nancy Hanks Lincoln, was a gentle and religious woman who taught him the value of honesty and compassion.<br><br>

            Lincoln‚Äôs childhood was filled with hardship. The family often struggled to survive, and Abraham had very little formal education. However, he had a strong desire to learn. He educated himself by reading borrowed books by the light of the fireplace after long days of farm work. His love of reading and thirst for knowledge became the foundation of his wisdom and leadership.<br><br>

            In 1830, the Lincoln family moved to Illinois, where Abraham worked various jobs ‚Äî as a rail-splitter, store clerk, and surveyor ‚Äî before studying law on his own. His honesty and fairness earned him the nickname ‚ÄúHonest Abe.‚Äù By 1836, he became a licensed lawyer and built a successful practice in Springfield, Illinois.<br><br>

            Lincoln entered politics in the 1830s, serving in the Illinois State Legislature and later in the U.S. House of Representatives. His strong opposition to the spread of slavery brought him national attention. In 1860, he was elected President of the United States, at a time when the nation was bitterly divided over the issue of slavery.<br><br>

            Shortly after his election, several southern states seceded from the Union, leading to the American Civil War (1861‚Äì1865). Despite facing enormous challenges, Lincoln remained firm in his belief that the Union must be preserved. He guided the country through its darkest hours with determination, wisdom, and compassion.<br><br>

            In 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared freedom for enslaved people in the Confederate states. This act transformed the war into a fight not only for unity but also for human liberty. Later, his famous speech, the Gettysburg Address, reminded Americans of the nation‚Äôs founding ideals ‚Äî equality, freedom, and democracy.<br><br>

            Lincoln was re-elected in 1864, but just as victory in the Civil War was near, tragedy struck. On April 14, 1865, while attending a play at Ford‚Äôs Theatre in Washington, D.C., he was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer. He died the following morning, leaving the entire nation in mourning.<br><br>

            Abraham Lincoln is remembered not only as the leader who preserved the Union and ended slavery but also as a man of great humility, courage, and moral strength. His life stands as a shining example of how determination, integrity, and compassion can overcome even the greatest obstacles.<br><br>

            His words ‚Äî ‚ÄúGovernment of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth‚Äù ‚Äî continue to inspire freedom and democracy around the world.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Dedan Kimathi</h2>

            Dedan Kimathi Waciuri was one of Kenya‚Äôs greatest freedom fighters and a symbol of resistance against British colonial rule. He was born on October 31, 1920, in Tetu, Nyeri County, in central Kenya. He came from a humble background and grew up in a time when the British controlled much of the land and the lives of Africans in Kenya.<br><br>

            Kimathi‚Äôs early life was marked by hard work and determination. He attended Karuna-ini and Tumutumu Mission Schools, where he performed well academically and showed strong leadership skills. However, due to financial difficulties, he could not continue his formal education. Despite this, he was known to be intelligent, outspoken, and deeply committed to justice.<br><br>

            As a young man, Kimathi worked as a teacher, clerk, and soldier, among other jobs. During this time, he became increasingly aware of the oppression and land injustices suffered by Africans under colonial rule. The fertile lands of central Kenya had been taken by white settlers, leaving Africans to live as laborers or squatters. This injustice inspired Kimathi to join the struggle for freedom.<br><br>

            He became a leading figure in the Mau Mau movement, which began in the 1950s. The movement sought to reclaim African land and independence through armed resistance. Dedan Kimathi was one of its most respected leaders, known for his courage, discipline, and strategic mind. He took the oath of unity and led many fighters into the forests of Mount Kenya and Aberdares, organizing the guerrilla warfare that challenged the British colonial government.<br><br>

            Kimathi was not just a fighter; he was also a thinker and a visionary. He believed in unity, discipline, and the moral strength of his people. He often spoke of freedom, justice, and the right of Africans to govern themselves. Despite being branded a ‚Äúterrorist‚Äù by the colonial authorities, to his people he was a hero and a symbol of resistance.<br><br>

            In October 1956, Dedan Kimathi was captured by the British forces after being shot in the leg. He was tried and later executed by hanging on February 18, 1957, at Kamiti Prison in Nairobi. His death was meant to break the spirit of the Mau Mau fighters, but instead, it strengthened the resolve of Kenyans to continue the fight for independence.<br><br>

            When Kenya finally gained independence in 1963, Kimathi‚Äôs dream was realized, even though he did not live to see it. Today, he is remembered as one of the most important figures in Kenya‚Äôs journey to freedom. Statues, roads, and institutions have been named in his honor, and his legacy continues to inspire generations to stand for justice and self-determination.<br><br>

            Dedan Kimathi‚Äôs life was one of courage, sacrifice, and unshakable belief in freedom. He showed that true leadership is not about power or wealth but about the willingness to fight for the dignity and rights of one‚Äôs people. His name remains forever etched in the history of Kenya as the spirit of the struggle for independence.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Nelson Mandela</h2>
      

            Nelson Rolihlahla Mandela was one of the greatest leaders of the 20th century and a symbol of peace, justice, and freedom. He was born on July 18, 1918, in the small village of Mvezo in the Eastern Cape Province of South Africa. His father, Gadla Henry Mphakanyiswa, was a local chief and counselor to the Thembu royal family, and his mother, Nosekeni Fanny, was a devout Christian who raised him with discipline and strong moral values.<br><br>

            Mandela‚Äôs birth name, Rolihlahla, means ‚Äúpulling the branch of a tree‚Äù or ‚Äútroublemaker.‚Äù Little did anyone know that he would grow up to challenge one of the most oppressive systems in the world. He attended missionary schools where teachers gave him the English name Nelson. He later studied at Fort Hare University and the University of Witwatersrand, where he became involved in the struggle against racial discrimination.<br><br>

            At that time, South Africa was under a brutal system of apartheid, which enforced racial segregation and denied basic rights to black citizens. Mandela joined the African National Congress (ANC) in 1944 and helped form its Youth League, aiming to unite Africans in the fight for equality and self-determination.<br><br>

            Mandela‚Äôs leadership and activism made him a target of the apartheid government. In 1962, he was arrested and later sentenced to life imprisonment for sabotage and conspiracy against the state. He spent 27 years in prison, mostly on Robben Island, enduring harsh conditions. Despite this, he never gave up his dream of a free and equal South Africa. He studied, wrote letters, and continued to inspire others from behind bars.<br><br>

            During his years in prison, Mandela became a global symbol of resistance and hope. People around the world demanded his release, and in 1990, he was finally freed. Instead of seeking revenge, he chose forgiveness and reconciliation, working to heal the wounds of a divided nation.<br><br>

            In 1994, Nelson Mandela made history when he became South Africa‚Äôs first black president in the country‚Äôs first democratic election. His leadership marked the beginning of a new era of unity, peace, and equality. He focused on rebuilding the nation, promoting reconciliation between blacks and whites, and laying the foundation for a democratic South Africa.<br><br>

            After serving one term as president, Mandela stepped down in 1999, showing that true leaders know when to pass on the torch. Even in retirement, he continued his humanitarian work through the Nelson Mandela Foundation, focusing on peace, education, and the fight against poverty and HIV/AIDS.<br><br>

            Nelson Mandela passed away on December 5, 2013, at the age of 95. The world mourned the loss of a man who had become a universal symbol of courage, forgiveness, and human dignity.<br><br>

            Mandela‚Äôs life teaches that freedom is achieved not through hatred or violence, but through patience, sacrifice, and compassion. His famous words ‚Äî ‚ÄúIt always seems impossible until it is done‚Äù ‚Äî continue to inspire people across the globe to stand up for what is right and to believe in the power of peace.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Aristotle</h2>

            Aristotle was one of the greatest philosophers and thinkers in history, whose ideas shaped Western thought for more than two thousand years. He was born in 384 BC in Stagira, a small town in Macedonia, northern Greece. His father, Nicomachus, was a physician to the royal court of Macedonia, which exposed young Aristotle to the study of nature and science from an early age.<br><br>

            When Aristotle was about seventeen years old, he traveled to Athens, the center of learning in ancient Greece, to study at Plato‚Äôs Academy, one of the most famous schools of philosophy in the world. He spent nearly twenty years there as a student and later as a teacher. Although Aristotle admired Plato greatly, he developed his own ways of thinking, often questioning and expanding on his teacher‚Äôs ideas.<br><br>

            After Plato‚Äôs death, Aristotle left Athens and spent some years traveling and studying different forms of government and life. Around 343 BC, he was invited by King Philip II of Macedonia to become the tutor of his young son, Alexander, who would later become known as Alexander the Great. Under Aristotle‚Äôs guidance, Alexander learned about philosophy, science, politics, and ethics.<br><br>

            Aristotle later returned to Athens and founded his own school, the Lyceum, where he taught and conducted research for over twelve years. His students were known as Peripatetics, meaning ‚Äúthose who walk about,‚Äù because Aristotle liked to teach while walking through the shaded paths of the Lyceum.<br><br>

            He studied a wide range of subjects ‚Äî including logic, biology, physics, politics, ethics, poetry, and metaphysics. He believed that knowledge should come from careful observation and reasoning, not just from theory. His method of thinking laid the foundation for the scientific method used today.<br><br>

            Some of his most famous works include ‚ÄúNicomachean Ethics,‚Äù ‚ÄúPolitics,‚Äù ‚ÄúPoetics,‚Äù ‚ÄúMetaphysics,‚Äù and ‚ÄúOn the Soul.‚Äù In these writings, Aristotle explored questions about human happiness, good government, art, and the nature of reality. He taught that the goal of human life is to achieve eudaimonia ‚Äî a state of happiness or fulfillment through virtue and wisdom.<br><br>

            Aristotle‚Äôs ideas deeply influenced later philosophers, scientists, and leaders. His teachings shaped the development of Western philosophy, science, and education for centuries. Even during the Middle Ages, his works were studied by great thinkers such as Thomas Aquinas, who called him simply ‚ÄúThe Philosopher.‚Äù<br><br>

            Aristotle passed away in 322 BC in Euboea, Greece, but his legacy has endured through the ages. His remarkable curiosity, logical thinking, and love for knowledge continue to inspire people around the world.<br><br>

            He once said, ‚ÄúWe are what we repeatedly do. Excellence, then, is not an act, but a habit.‚Äù These words perfectly describe his own life ‚Äî a life devoted to learning, teaching, and the pursuit of truth.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Kwame Nkrumah</h2>

            Kwame Nkrumah was one of Africa‚Äôs greatest leaders and a key figure in the continent‚Äôs struggle for independence and unity. He was born on September 21, 1909, in Nkroful, a small village in the Gold Coast (now Ghana). He came from a humble background and was raised in a traditional family that valued education, hard work, and faith.<br><br>

            Nkrumah began his education at a local Catholic school, where he showed great intelligence and discipline. His teachers recognized his potential and encouraged him to pursue further studies. After completing his early education, he attended Achimota School in Accra, one of the most prestigious institutions in the colony. There, he was inspired by ideas of freedom, equality, and African pride.<br><br>

            In 1935, Nkrumah traveled to the United States to further his studies. He enrolled at Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, where he earned a Bachelor‚Äôs degree in Economics and Sociology, and later a Master‚Äôs degree in Education and Philosophy from the University of Pennsylvania. While in America, he became deeply interested in Pan-Africanism ‚Äî the idea that all Africans, both on the continent and in the diaspora, should unite for political and economic independence. He was influenced by great Black leaders such as Marcus Garvey and W.E.B. Du Bois.<br><br>

            After completing his studies, Nkrumah moved to London in 1945, where he continued his political work. He helped organize the 5th Pan-African Congress, which called for the end of colonial rule in Africa. In 1947, he returned to the Gold Coast and joined the United Gold Coast Convention (UGCC), a political party that demanded self-government. However, Nkrumah‚Äôs passion and radical approach soon led him to form his own party ‚Äî the Convention People‚Äôs Party (CPP) ‚Äî in 1949.<br><br>

            Nkrumah‚Äôs message of ‚ÄúSelf-Government Now!‚Äù inspired millions of Ghanaians. He led mass protests, strikes, and campaigns demanding freedom from British colonial rule. In 1950, he was imprisoned by the colonial authorities for his political activities, but even from prison, his popularity continued to grow.<br><br>

            In 1951, while still in jail, Nkrumah‚Äôs party won a major victory in the country‚Äôs first general elections, and he was released to become Leader of Government Business. By 1957, his dream was realized when the Gold Coast became the independent nation of Ghana, the first country in sub-Saharan Africa to gain independence. Nkrumah became its first Prime Minister and later its first President.<br><br>

            As President, Nkrumah worked to modernize Ghana by building schools, roads, industries, and hospitals. He promoted education, African unity, and socialism, believing that Africa could only prosper through cooperation and self-reliance. In 1963, he helped establish the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which later became the African Union (AU).<br><br>

            However, his leadership also faced challenges. Economic difficulties, political tensions, and growing opposition weakened his government. In 1966, while he was on a state visit to China and North Vietnam, his government was overthrown in a military coup. He lived the rest of his life in exile in Guinea, where he was honored as a co-president by his friend Ahmed S√©kou Tour√©.<br><br>

            Kwame Nkrumah died on April 27, 1972, in Bucharest, Romania, after a long illness. Although he did not live to see his dream of a united Africa fulfilled, his vision and ideals continue to inspire generations.<br><br>

            Nkrumah is remembered as the founding father of Ghana and one of the greatest Pan-African leaders in history. His famous words ‚Äî ‚ÄúThe independence of Ghana is meaningless unless it is linked up with the total liberation of Africa‚Äù ‚Äî remind Africans of the importance of unity, freedom, and self-determination.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Alexander the Great</h2>

            Alexander the Great was one of the most remarkable military leaders in history and one of the greatest conquerors the world has ever known. He was born in 356 BC in Pella, the ancient capital of Macedonia, a kingdom in northern Greece. His father, King Philip II, was a powerful ruler and a brilliant general who united most of the Greek city-states under his control. His mother, Queen Olympias, was a deeply spiritual and ambitious woman who believed her son was destined for greatness.<br><br>

            From a young age, Alexander showed exceptional intelligence, courage, and determination. When he was just thirteen, his father hired Aristotle, the famous Greek philosopher, as his tutor. Under Aristotle‚Äôs guidance, Alexander studied philosophy, science, politics, literature, and ethics. These lessons helped shape his thinking and his respect for knowledge, culture, and leadership.<br><br>

            At the age of sixteen, Alexander was already commanding troops and showing great skill as a military leader. When his father was assassinated in 336 BC, Alexander became king of Macedonia at only twenty years old. Despite his youth, he quickly proved his strength and leadership. He united the Greek states and set out on an ambitious mission ‚Äî to conquer the vast Persian Empire, which was the most powerful empire in the world at that time.<br><br>

            Over the next decade, Alexander led his army through a series of brilliant military campaigns that took him across Asia Minor, Egypt, Persia, and even into India. His strategy, courage, and loyalty inspired his soldiers to achieve what seemed impossible. He never lost a battle, earning him the title ‚ÄúAlexander the Great.‚Äù<br><br>

            One of his most famous victories was the Battle of Issus (333 BC) against the Persian king Darius III, and later the Battle of Gaugamela (331 BC), which led to the fall of the Persian Empire. In Egypt, he was welcomed as a liberator and founded the city of Alexandria, which later became a great center of learning and culture.<br><br>

            Alexander dreamed not only of conquering lands but also of uniting the peoples of the world. He encouraged cultural exchange, intermarriage between Greeks and Persians, and respect for different religions and traditions. He saw himself as a bridge between East and West, aiming to create a single world under harmony and understanding.<br><br>

            However, his long campaigns took a heavy toll on his soldiers and on his own health. In 323 BC, while planning further conquests in Arabia, Alexander fell ill in the city of Babylon and died at the young age of 32. His death left his vast empire without a clear successor, and it was eventually divided among his generals.<br><br>

            Despite his short life, Alexander‚Äôs legacy lived on for centuries. He spread Greek culture, language, and ideas across three continents ‚Äî from Greece to Egypt, Persia, and India ‚Äî a period known as the Hellenistic Age. Cities he founded became centers of learning and civilization.<br><br>

            Alexander the Great is remembered not only as a brilliant military genius but also as a visionary leader who dreamed of unity, knowledge, and cultural exchange. His life remains a powerful example of ambition, courage, and the desire to leave a lasting mark on the world.<br><br>

            He once said, ‚ÄúThere is nothing impossible to him who will try.‚Äù These words continue to inspire people everywhere to pursue greatness through courage, vision, and determination.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Raila Odinga</h2>

            Raila Amolo Odinga is one of Kenya‚Äôs most influential political leaders, known for his lifelong struggle for democracy, justice, and good governance. He was born on January 7, 1945, in Maseno, in Kisumu County, Kenya. His father, Jaramogi Oginga Odinga, was a respected freedom fighter and Kenya‚Äôs first Vice President after independence, while his mother, Mary Juma Odinga, was a devoted and caring woman who valued education and discipline.<br><br>

            Raila grew up in a politically active family that believed strongly in freedom and equality. He attended Maranda Primary and Secondary Schools before joining the Herder Institute in East Germany and later the Technical University of Magdeburg, where he studied Mechanical Engineering. His years abroad opened his mind to new political ideas, especially the importance of social justice, democracy, and economic equality.<br><br>

            AfRaila Odingater returning to Kenya in the early 1970s, Raila became a lecturer at the University of Nairobi and later ventured into business and politics. However, he soon became deeply involved in the struggle for multi-party democracy, opposing the one-party rule of the Kenya African National Union (KANU) under President Daniel arap Moi.<br><br>

            In 1982, following a failed coup attempt against the government, Raila was accused of being part of the plot and was detained without trial for several years. Despite facing imprisonment and torture, he never gave up his dream of a free and democratic Kenya. His courage and resilience earned him national and international recognition as a symbol of resistance and reform.<br><br>

            After his release, Raila continued to fight for political change. He became a key leader in the Forum for the Restoration of Democracy (FORD) movement in the early 1990s, which helped bring an end to one-party rule. He later founded and led the National Development Party (NDP) and played a vital role in shaping Kenya‚Äôs new political landscape.<br><br>

            Throughout his career, Raila has served the Kenyan people in various capacities. He was elected Member of Parliament for Lang‚Äôata Constituency and later appointed Minister for Energy (2001‚Äì2002) and Minister for Roads, Public Works, and Housing (2003‚Äì2005). He was instrumental in introducing reforms and promoting development in these sectors.<br><br>

            In 2007, Raila contested for the presidency under the Orange Democratic Movement (ODM). The disputed election results led to widespread unrest, which ended after a power-sharing agreement was reached in 2008. Under this arrangement, Raila Odinga became Kenya‚Äôs second Prime Minister, serving alongside President Mwai Kibaki in a coalition government. During his tenure, he focused on national reconciliation, infrastructure development, and the implementation of the 2010 Constitution, one of Kenya‚Äôs most important reforms.<br><br>

            Raila has remained a key figure in Kenyan politics, running for the presidency several times ‚Äî in 1997, 2007, 2013, 2017, and 2022. Despite not yet becoming president, his influence on Kenya‚Äôs democracy and governance is undeniable. He continues to advocate for transparency, unity, and equal opportunity for all Kenyans.<br><br>

            Beyond politics, Raila Odinga is also known for his love of sports, especially football, and for promoting peace and African unity. His resilience and belief in justice have earned him respect both in Kenya and across Africa.<br><br>

            Raila‚Äôs life is a story of courage, endurance, and unwavering hope. He has faced imprisonment, political defeat, and personal loss, yet he continues to stand for the principles of democracy and freedom.<br>

            He once said, ‚ÄúThe struggle for justice and democracy never ends; it is a continuous journey.‚Äù His life reminds Kenyans and the world that true leadership is not about power, but about serving the people with courage, vision, and integrity.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Haile Selassie I</h2>

            Haile Selassie I was one of Africa‚Äôs most influential and respected leaders ‚Äî an emperor, reformer, and symbol of unity and independence. He was born on July 23, 1892, in Ejersa Goro, near Harar, in Ethiopia. His birth name was Tafari Makonnen. His father, Ras Makonnen Woldemikael, was a governor and a trusted general under Emperor Menelik II, while his mother, Yeshimebet Ali, came from a noble family. From a young age, Tafari was known for his intelligence, discipline, and leadership qualities.<br><br>

            He received an excellent education for his time, studying languages, religion, and politics. His sharp mind and dedication quickly earned him recognition within the royal court. In 1916, after the removal of Emperor Lij Iyasu, Tafari was appointed Regent and Heir to the Throne of Ethiopia. When Empress Zewditu died in 1930, Tafari was crowned Emperor Haile Selassie I, meaning ‚ÄúPower of the Trinity.‚Äù His coronation drew attention from around the world and marked a new era for Ethiopia.<br><br>

            As emperor, Haile Selassie was determined to modernize his country while preserving its ancient culture and independence. He introduced progressive reforms, including the 1931 Constitution, which established Ethiopia‚Äôs first parliament. He also worked to expand education, strengthen the legal system, and improve infrastructure. His vision was to lead Ethiopia into the modern world while maintaining its sovereignty.<br><br>

            In 1935, Ethiopia faced one of its darkest moments when it was invaded by Fascist Italy under Benito Mussolini. Haile Selassie led his people in resistance, but the Italian forces eventually occupied the country. Forced into exile, he traveled to Europe to seek international support. In 1936, he addressed the League of Nations in Geneva, delivering one of the most powerful speeches in modern history. He pleaded for justice and warned the world that the aggression against Ethiopia was a threat to all nations. His words ‚Äî ‚ÄúIt is us today. It will be you tomorrow.‚Äù ‚Äî became prophetic during World War II.<br><br>

            In 1941, with the help of Allied forces, Haile Selassie returned triumphantly to Ethiopia, restoring its independence. He continued his reforms, strengthening education, introducing new industries, and expanding diplomatic relations. He became a symbol of African unity and independence, inspiring liberation movements across the continent.<br><br>

            Haile Selassie played a major role in the creation of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in 1963, which later became the African Union (AU). He firmly believed that Africans must unite to achieve peace, freedom, and development. His Pan-African vision earned him deep respect across the world.<br><br>

            To many people, especially followers of the Rastafari movement in Jamaica and other parts of the world, Haile Selassie was seen as a divine figure ‚Äî a living symbol of African pride, dignity, and redemption. Though he never claimed divinity himself, he inspired a global movement that continues to honor his legacy.<br><br>

            In his later years, Ethiopia faced economic challenges, political unrest, and famine. In 1974, Haile Selassie was overthrown by the military after ruling for more than forty years. He was placed under house arrest and died the following year, in 1975, under unclear circumstances.<br><br>

            Despite his fall from power, Haile Selassie‚Äôs legacy endures. He is remembered as a visionary leader, a unifier, and a defender of African independence. His reign helped transform Ethiopia into a respected member of the global community.<br><br>

            Haile Selassie once said, ‚ÄúThroughout history, it has been the inaction of those who could have acted that has made it possible for evil to triumph.‚Äù His life stands as a powerful reminder of the importance of courage, leadership, and the belief in justice and human dignity.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Julius Nyerere</h2>

            Julius Kambarage Nyerere, affectionately known as Mwalimu (meaning Teacher), was the founding father of Tanzania and one of Africa‚Äôs most respected leaders. He was born on April 13, 1922, in Butiama, near Lake Victoria, in what was then Tanganyika. His father, Chi<br>ef Nyerere Burito, was the local Zanaki chief, and his mother, Christina Mugaya, was one of his many wives. From his humble rural beginnings, Julius Nyerere rose to become one of the most visionary and unifying figures in Africa‚Äôs history.<br><br>

            Nyerere began his education at local mission schools, where he quickly showed intelligence, discipline, and curiosity. His academic excellence earned him a place at Makerere College in Uganda, one of East Africa‚Äôs leading institutions. Later, he won a scholarship to study in the United Kingdom, becoming the first Tanganyikan to earn a university degree when he graduated from the University of Edinburgh with a Bachelor of Arts in Economics and History in 1952.<br><br>

            Upon returning home, he worked as a teacher, earning the nickname Mwalimu ‚Äî a title that would stay with him for life. However, his growing concern for his people‚Äôs political and social conditions led him into activism. At the time, Tanganyika was still under British colonial rule, and Nyerere believed that education and unity were the keys to independence.<br><br>

            In 1954, he founded the Tanganyika African National Union (TANU), a political movement dedicated to achieving independence through peaceful means. His leadership, humility, and persuasive speeches inspired millions of Tanganyikans to support the cause. Through determination and diplomacy, Nyerere guided the nation toward freedom, and on December 9, 1961, Tanganyika became independent, with Nyerere as its first Prime Minister.<br><br>

            Three years later, Tanganyika united with Zanzibar to form the United Republic of Tanzania, and Nyerere became its first President. His vision for Tanzania was based on African socialism, known as Ujamaa, meaning ‚Äúfamilyhood.‚Äù Through this philosophy, he promoted unity, equality, self-reliance, and rural development. He encouraged Tanzanians to live and work together in cooperative communities, believing that the strength of the nation lay in shared responsibility and compassion.<br><br>

            Nyerere was deeply committed to education and believed it was the foundation of progress. Under his leadership, Tanzania made remarkable advances in literacy and healthcare. Though his socialist economic policies faced challenges, his moral leadership and integrity earned him great respect both at home and across Africa.<br><br>

            On the international stage, Nyerere was a strong advocate for Pan-Africanism and the liberation of Africa from colonialism. He supported independence movements in countries such as Zimbabwe, Mozambique, and South Africa. He was also one of the founders of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), the predecessor of today‚Äôs African Union (AU).<br><br>

            After serving as President for more than two decades, Nyerere voluntarily stepped down in 1985, setting an example of peaceful leadership transition ‚Äî a rare act among leaders of his era. Even in retirement, he continued to play an active role in mediating peace efforts across Africa.<br><br>

            Julius Nyerere passed away on October 14, 1999, in London, after a lifetime devoted to service, unity, and equality. He remains a national hero of Tanzania and a symbol of African dignity, wisdom, and moral leadership.<br><br>

            He once said, ‚ÄúEducation is not a way to escape poverty; it is a way of fighting it.‚Äù His life and words continue to inspire people across Africa to lead with honesty, humility, and a spirit of service.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Martin Luther King Jr.</h2>

            Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was one of the most influential leaders in modern history ‚Äî a preacher, activist, and visionary who devoted his life to the struggle for civil rights, justice, and equality. He was born on January 15, 1929, in Atlanta, Georgia, USA, into a deeply religious family. His father, Martin Luther King Sr., was a respected Baptist minister, and his mother, Alberta Williams King, was a schoolteacher. From a young age, Martin was taught the values of faith, hard work, and compassion.<br><br>

            He attended Morehouse College, one of the leading historically Black universities in America, where he studied sociology and began developing his deep interest in social justice. After graduating in 1948, he went on to study theology at Crozer Theological Seminary in Pennsylvania, where he distinguished himself as an excellent student and an inspiring speaker. Later, he earned a Ph.D. in Systematic Theology from Boston University in 1955.<br><br>

            While studying in Boston, he met and married Coretta Scott, who shared his passion for justice and peace. Together, they would raise four children and dedicate their lives to the fight against racial discrimination.<br><br>

            In 1954, King became the pastor of Dexter Avenue Baptist Church in Montgomery, Alabama. A year later, he was thrust into national prominence when he led the Montgomery Bus Boycott, sparked by the arrest of Rosa Parks, an African American woman who refused to give up her seat to a white passenger. The boycott lasted over a year and ended in victory, marking the beginning of the modern Civil Rights Movement.<br><br>

            Dr. King believed in nonviolent resistance, inspired by the teachings of Mahatma Gandhi. He taught that love and peaceful protest were stronger than hatred and violence. Through his leadership, he organized marches, boycotts, and speeches that challenged segregation and inspired millions to join the fight for justice.<br><br>

            One of his most memorable moments came on August 28, 1963, during the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, where he delivered his legendary ‚ÄúI Have a Dream‚Äù speech before more than 250,000 people. In that speech, he envisioned a world where people would be judged by ‚Äúthe content of their character, not the color of their skin.‚Äù<br><br>

            His tireless efforts led to major legal and social changes, including the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which outlawed racial segregation and protected African Americans‚Äô right to vote. That same year, King was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for his commitment to nonviolence and equality ‚Äî becoming one of the youngest recipients in history.<br><br>

            However, his activism also made him a target of hatred and violence. Despite threats and arrests, he continued to speak out against racism, poverty, and war, expanding his vision to include global peace and economic justice.<br><br>

            On April 4, 1968, while in Memphis, Tennessee, to support striking sanitation workers, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was assassinated. His death shocked the world, but his dream lived on.<br><br>

            Dr. King‚Äôs legacy continues to shape societies worldwide. His words and actions inspired generations to stand up for justice through peace and courage. His birthday, January 15, is now celebrated each year in the United States as Martin Luther King Jr. Day, a national holiday honoring his life and message.<br><br>

            He once said, ‚ÄúInjustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.‚Äù Those words continue to remind the world that the fight for equality is not only for one nation or race but for all humanity.<br><br>
    </section>

    <section class="bio">
      <h2>Mother Teresa</h2>

            Mother Teresa, born Anjez√´ Gonxhe Bojaxhiu on August 26, 1910, in Skopje (now part of North Macedonia), was one of the most compassionate and selfless humanitarians in modern history. From a young age, she felt a deep calling to serve others, inspired by her strong faith and the example of her devout Catholic family.<br><br>

            At the age of 18, she joined the Sisters of Loreto and traveled to India, where she began teaching at St. Mary‚Äôs High School in Calcutta (now Kolkata). Although she loved her teaching work, she soon felt another, stronger call ‚Äî to serve ‚Äúthe poorest of the poor.‚Äù<br><br>

            In 1948, Mother Teresa left her convent and began working in the slums of Calcutta, tending to the sick, the dying, and the destitute. With compassion as her guiding light, she founded the **Missionaries of Charity** in 1950, a religious congregation devoted to caring for those in need ‚Äî the hungry, the homeless, and the forgotten.<br><br>

            Her simple blue-and-white sari became a symbol of peace and service. Through her organization, Mother Teresa established orphanages, hospices, and leprosy centers around the world, bringing dignity and comfort to millions of suffering people. Her tireless work earned her global admiration and recognition.<br><br>

            Despite her fame, Mother Teresa lived a life of humility. She often said, ‚ÄúNot all of us can do great things. But we can do small things with great love.‚Äù Her mission was never about wealth or power but about love and compassion for every human being, regardless of race, religion, or background.<br><br>

            In 1979, she was awarded the **Nobel Peace Prize** for her humanitarian efforts. Even as she aged and her health declined, she continued to travel and serve others until her death on **September 5, 1997**. Her legacy lives on through the Missionaries of Charity, which continues her work in more than 130 countries.<br><br>

            Mother Teresa was canonized as a saint by the Roman Catholic Church on **September 4, 2016**, and is now known as **Saint Teresa of Calcutta**.<br><br>

            Her life reminds the world that true greatness is found not in power or fame, but in love, kindness, and service to others.<br><br>
    </section>

